turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail added a second Scooby van, a GMC version, to her motorcade in Iowa. The two identical vehicles have raised roofs, deep-tinted windows, and New York license plates, but one has a mustard-yellow tag and the other has blue and white plates of a different design. The use of decoy vehicles is common for the Secret Service to inject mystery into VIPs' travel plans and confuse potential attackers. The two Scooby vans arrived at Clinton's location separately but left together in a seven-car motorcade, which also included four black Suburbans, a white minivan, and a GMC van with blue and red flashing lights.

A Georgia mother of six, Kalimah Dixon, is seeking help after a fire destroyed her rented condo, leaving her family homeless and without possessions. The fire occurred early Monday morning, and Dixon was able to safely evacuate her children, aged one to 14. She has been unable to find a new permanent home due to being unemployed and currently staying with a friend far from her children's schools. Dixon had quit her job four years ago to pursue a degree in business management. Her children are set to take a standardized test on Tuesday, but she is unsure of their living situation. Dixon has started a GoFundMe page that has raised over $4,600 in donations so far. She is asking for assistance and prayers as her family tries to recover from this devastating loss.

An Australian couple abandoned a boy born through a surrogacy deal in India, leaving him stateless, according to new evidence. Documents obtained by the ABC reveal that Australian government officials were aware of the situation and that the couple was from New South Wales, where international surrogacy arrangements are illegal. The couple traveled to India in late 2012 and sought citizenship for a baby girl, but told consular staff they would be leaving her twin brother behind because they could not afford him. They planned to give the boy to friends in India who were unable to conceive. The couple was warned that the boy would be left stateless if they followed through with their plans, as India does not recognize surrogate children as citizens. There were concerns last year that the boy may have been sold, and the Chief Justice of the Family Court expressed concerns about the situation, calling it "trafficking children" and a breach of human rights conventions. The case is similar to the recent baby Gammy case, where an Australian couple left a child born through a surrogate mother in Thailand.

Kecil, a baby orangutan, had a difficult start to life after being rejected by his natural mother and a surrogate mother. However, he found a loving home with Maggie, an experienced orangutan mother at Chicago's Brookfield Zoo. Maggie has been raising Kecil for the past 10 months, and the two have a strong bond. Zookeepers were initially worried that Maggie might reject Kecil, but she has proven her parenting skills once again. Kecil was initially moved to different zoos and given to different surrogate mothers, but he was ultimately taken in by Maggie. The pair showed signs of intimacy from the beginning, but keepers had to wait to see if Maggie would fully take on parental duties. A turning point came when a fire alarm scared Kecil, and he ran to Maggie for comfort.

After settling into their new enclosure, Kecil will be on display for the first time this weekend for two-hour slots between 10 am and midday, allowing him to nap in the afternoons. Keepers say that Kecil and Maggie have learned to stick close to one another, and the pair will eventually join the zoo's other orangutans in an exhibit. For now, they are living in isolation, as would be the case in the wild. Keepers are excited to see Kecil's progress and how he interacts with the other orangutans when they are eventually introduced.

Javier Pastore, a Paris Saint-Germain star, has dismissed Eric Cantona's claim that he is the greatest footballer on the planet. Cantona, a former Manchester United forward, had praised Pastore as "the best player in the world," but Pastore believes Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. Pastore scored a brace in PSG's 3-1 win at Nice on Saturday, helping the team reclaim top spot in Ligue 1. PSG face Barcelona in the second leg of their last-eight Champions League tie on Tuesday, needing to overcome a 3-1 deficit to progress to the semi-finals.

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife, has successfully campaigned for a change in the practice of cord clamping in childbirth. Traditionally, doctors and midwives have clamped the cord within seconds of delivery, but Burleigh believed this was harmful to the baby and not grounded in evidence. She and her colleagues amassed evidence that early cord clamping could be harmful, particularly for premature babies, raising the risk of iron deficiency anemia and other issues.

After years of resistance from colleagues, Burleigh and her team finally convinced the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to change its guidelines. NICE now recommends that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby, and the cord should be clamped within five minutes, or longer if the mother requests. This change not only provides medical benefits but also allows mothers to hold their babies while still connected to them.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to show no mercy if French peacekeepers in the Central African Republic are found guilty of raping hungry children in exchange for food. A French judicial source has revealed that 14 soldiers dispatched to restore order after a 2013 coup have been accused of abusing children as young as nine. The investigation has been underway since last year, but was only made public recently. The French defense ministry has denied covering up the scandal and urged caution, as the accusations have not yet been proven. A UN employee accused of leaking a report on the abuse has been suspended. The violence in the Central African Republic has largely pitted the Christian majority against mainly Muslim Seleka rebels who led the March 2013 coup against former leader Francois Bozize.

A shocking "resurrection ceremony" for a two-year-old dead boy was caught on camera at a Texas church. Aracely Meza, the pastor's wife, was arrested and charged with injury to a child by omission. The child, identified as Benjamin, was reportedly possessed by demons, according to pastors. The ceremony took place at a home that also operated as a church, presided by Aracely and her husband, Daniel Meza. The child had allegedly gone 25 days without food before he died. The home was not registered or zoned to operate as a church, and its national headquarters are at the home's address. Police received an anonymous tip four days after the ceremony and discovered that the child's body had been taken to Mexico. The child's parents took the body to Mexico the following day, and police are now investigating.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott, both from Scotland, had a successful day at the Betfred World Championship on Sunday. Higgins, a four-time winner, defeated Robert Milkins 10-5, while Dott, an unseeded player, beat Ricky Walden 10-8. Higgins, who last won the title four years ago, showed impressive form and is now considering the possibility of winning the championship again. Dott, who won the title in 2006, also played well and advanced to the next round. Both players will continue to compete in the tournament, with Higgins aiming to match Ronnie O'Sullivan's five world titles.

Barcelona stars Neymar, Dani Alves, and Adriano were delighted with their team's victory over Celta Vigo in La Liga, despite their questionable choice of matching denim outfits. The Brazilians played crucial roles in the hard-fought win, which saw Barcelona return to the summit of La Liga. Game winner Jeremy Mathieu admitted that his side had a poor performance, attributing it to the international break, but praised the defensive efforts of Gerard Pique.

Chelsea manager Jose Mourinho is planning to sign Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke this summer, with the club's technical director Michael Emenalo recently watching Koke play. Mourinho may offer second-choice left-back Filipe Luis as part of the deal, as Koke has a release clause of around £50 million. Koke, an Atletico academy graduate, has been instrumental in the team's success, including their run to the Champions League final last season.

Tom Ballard, a renowned climber, plans to climb K2, 20 years after his mother Alison Hargreaves died descending from the peak. He was six years old when his mother died, and now sees it as his destiny to follow in her footsteps. Last month, Ballard became the first to solo climb all six of the great north faces of the Alps in the winter season, and now he is training for K2. The mountain is considered more difficult to reach than Mount Everest, with dozens dying during attempts to reach the top. Ballard's mother was a revered figure in the climbing world and was only the second person to climb Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen. She died in 1995 during her descent from K2, leaving behind her husband and two children. Ballard has clear memories of climbing as a child and always knew it was his calling. He now aims to conquer K2, following in his mother's footsteps and honoring her legacy.

A consortium of companies has claimed that there could be up to 100 billion barrels of oil beneath the Home Counties in an area called "Britain's Dallas." The potential oil reserves, located in the Weald Basin across Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire, and Kent, could reportedly meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. The discovery, made by UK Oil & Gas Investments at the Horse Hill site near Gatwick Airport, has been called "world-class" and could be a major boost for British industry. However, industry experts remain skeptical, with some describing the claims as "overly optimistic."

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls, citing lack of evidence for effectiveness and humaneness. They recommend completing the pilot culls in Somerset and Gloucestershire by trapping badgers in cages and then shooting them. The BVA still supports badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. Animal welfare campaigners welcomed the news but expressed regret over the BVA's ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting. Environment Secretary Liz Truss promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election, citing decreased TB incidence on farms in pilot areas. The BVA's withdrawal of support comes after the second year of culling in Gloucestershire fell short of the minimum number of badgers needed to deliver TB reductions in livestock. The government claimed low numbers were due to extensive unlawful protest and intimidation by anti-cull campaigners. In Somerset, a sufficient number of badgers were killed this year to lead to expected reductions in TB in cattle.

Modern technology, while intended to make life easier, often creates more pitfalls in relationships. Smartphones and social media can cause problems on dates, such as constantly checking phones, taking photos of food, or immediately changing relationship statuses on Facebook. To avoid these issues, Blu e-cigarettes suggests tips like leaving phones off the table, not taking food photos, and not updating relationship statuses too soon. It's also important to avoid discussing Tinder, using Snapchat to update friends, and not bragging about past matches. Finally, it's best to leave Google Glass at home.

Ahead of this weekend's Premier League action, Sportsmail provides team news, provisional squads, betting odds, and Opta stats for Tottenham's home clash with Aston Villa.

* Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris are absent, while Jan Vertonghen is a doubt.

Aston Villa:

A mother named Jaye Cox made the heartbreaking decision to give birth to her sick baby, Annabelle, at 20 weeks when scans showed she had a serious form of Spina Bifida. After Annabelle's premature birth, her parents contacted Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization that transforms donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who pass away too soon. Angel Gowns created a dress from Jaye's wedding gown for Annabelle to be buried in, allowing her parents and siblings to spend time with her before her funeral. The organization currently donates outfits to over 80 hospitals and funeral homes across Australia and works directly with families and various children's charities. To donate a wedding dress or volunteer with Angel Gowns, visit [www.angelgownprogram.com.au](http://www.angelgownprogram.com.au).

PC Ronnie Lungu, a black police constable, has won a race discrimination case against Wiltshire Police. The tribunal found that he was passed over for promotion due to his race, with his internal assessments being secretly downgraded to make him appear unworthy. The force is said to have taken derogatory comments about Mr. Lungu based on his color, violating his dignity. When he raised concerns, they were not taken seriously, and his complaints were brushed off as trivial. The force, which has only 16 ethnic minority officers out of a total of just over 1,000, denied the claims. However, the tribunal ruled that Mr. Lungu was unlawfully discriminated against on grounds of race. Mr. Lungu expressed his anger and upset at the discrimination and hopes that Wiltshire Police will take the issue seriously and implement new procedures to tackle discrimination. The Chief Constable of Wiltshire Police, Patrick Geenty, said the force was "concerned" by the findings and would "learn lessons" from the case.

American YouTube user KentuckyFriedIdiot taught his newborn daughter to suck a plastic water bottle, with the adorable moment captured on camera. The video shows the father gnawing on the bottle, then stopping and prompting his child to follow. The infant quickly mimics him, sucking on her own bottle. The duo then enjoys bonding time together with their simple props. The video has received over 190,000 views, with many viewers finding it "cute" and "adorable."

A collection of rare photographs taken by Hugh Owen between 1850 and 1855 captures Bristol at the dawn of photography. The images, which could fetch up to £30,000 at auction, showcase the city's waterfront, city center, St Mary Redcliffe church, and other landmarks. Many of the buildings have since undergone significant changes, particularly High Street, which was heavily bombed during World War II. Some areas, like St John's Gate at the Church of St John the Baptist, have remained largely unchanged. The albumen prints were made in the 1870s from Owen's original paper negatives and offer a fascinating glimpse into Bristol's history.

Pro-Ukip businessman Harvey Boulter, who forced Liam Fox to resign as Defence Secretary, is funding the Ukip candidate opposing Fox in Somerset and spending another £30,000 to defeat "golden boy" Tory candidate Tom Tugendhat in Kent. Boulter's vendetta stems from a High Court case in which Tugendhat's father, Sir Michael Tugendhat, awarded Fox a six-figure sum in damages after Boulter made libellous remarks about Fox on Sky TV. Boulter admitted that his actions may seem like "naked revenge," but insisted that he was outraged by the court case outcome. A Tory Party spokesman declined to comment on the matter.

Aston Villa manager Tim Sherwood replied to a letter from 6-year-old Charlie Pye, who had applied for the Villa manager position. Sherwood congratulated Charlie on his credentials and encouraged him in his football career. Charlie, who is captain of Norton Lindsey, had offered to appoint his parents as assistant managers and provide bacon sandwiches for the players. Sherwood has guided Villa to six points above the relegation zone and an FA Cup semi-final against Liverpool.

Atletico Madrid defeated bottom side Cordoba 2-0 with Antoine Griezmann scoring the opener, helping his team leapfrog Valencia in the battle for La Liga's third automatic Champions League berth. The victory took Atletico to 62 points from 29 matches, ahead of Valencia on 60 points. Valencia can reclaim third spot with a win against Villarreal on Sunday. Saul Niguez scored Atletico's second goal, ensuring his side's victory. Valencia are two points behind Atletico but have a game in hand. Cordoba suffered their 10th consecutive defeat and are close to equaling the worst run in Spain's top flight. Atletico also stayed close to Real Madrid, who have 64 points, four behind leaders Barcelona.

An 18-year-old mother-of-one, Abby Swinfield, from Castle Donington, Derbyshire, died after taking M-Cat at a house party in Tamworth. She was rushed to the hospital in the early hours of March 30 and placed in a coma, but died a week later. Her cousin claims her drink was spiked, and police have arrested a 20-year-old girl on suspicion of supplying Class B drugs. Abby's mother, Kay, is devastated by her daughter's death, which was caused by multiple organ failure after suffering two heart attacks. Abby had a son, believed to be three years old, who keeps asking for his mother. Police are still waiting for the result of the post-mortem but believe the teenager had taken the illegal Class B drug Mephedrone, also known as MCat or Meow Meow.

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, raising concerns for the health of children in the area. Soil underneath a slide at the park in Toshima ward showed radiation readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour, nearly half the recommended annual limit. Authorities believe the radiation could be coming from something buried underneath the park and have cordoned off the area. The city has set up a health advice office to address concerns from parents. Japan has seen heightened concern over radiation since the 2011 Fukushima disaster. In related news, a drone with a small amount of radiation was found on Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's office building this week.

Amir Khan believes Kell Brook is only calling him out for a big payday, and that Brook's opponents are not as strong as he claims. Khan has agreed to fight Chris Algieri, but denied that the fight is happening next month, claiming there are other options. Khan also believes Brook is not a big name in the UK or the US, and that he doesn't need to fight Brook to make money. Khan intends to fight Brook within the next 12 months, but Brook is hoping for the fight to happen sooner.

A Dallas architect has transformed 14 shipping containers into a stunningly modern 3,700-square-foot three-bedroom home called 'PV14'. The home features a 1,400 sq ft roof deck, a 40ft long swimming pool, and a 360-degree view of White Rock Lake and downtown Dallas. Architect Michael Gooden worked with Matt Mooney on the project, aiming to stay true to the shipping container materials. The ceilings were left exposed, and the container gates remained unpainted. Columns were added to restore structural integrity, and spray foam insulation was used. The house includes a glass-paneled tower that reflects the long, slim pool. The open-floor first level has polished cement matching the shipping containers' steel overhead. The upstairs levels have maple wood floors, complementing the views of the nearby park and lake. Deep porches protect the home from direct sunlight while allowing natural light to seep in. Mooney, who had dreamed of building a shipping container home for 25 years, finally found the perfect spot in the same neighborhood where he and his wife Barbara, a retired nurse, had lived for 23 years. After more than two years of design and construction, the couple are preparing to move into their unique new home.

Jordon Ibe is set to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool by the end of the week, keeping him at the club until 2020. The 19-year-old has made a notable impact in his eight appearances since returning from a loan spell at Derby County. Liverpool also expects to announce Jordan Henderson's new contract this week and is close to finalizing an extension for Martin Skrtel. Talks are ongoing with young defender Jon Flanagan, whose contract expires in June. Additionally, Liverpool has agreed a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Standard Chartered worth around £30million a year.

Comedian Rik Mayall, who died suddenly last June, failed to leave a valid will to deal with his £1.2 million estate. This could result in a large inheritance tax bill for his family, as well as complications in dividing his estate according to government intestacy rules. Mayall, known for his role as scheming Tory MP Alan B’Stard in ITV series The New Statesman, did not have a will despite suffering serious head injuries in a 1998 quad-bike accident. His wife of 29 years, Barbara, and their three adult children could face tax pitfalls due to the lack of a will.

Experts have always advised people to have a valid will to avoid such issues. Mayall's children would be entitled to a share of his net estate, which could be liable for inheritance tax depending on the value of his chattels or personal belongings. His widow would receive £250,000 and all his chattels under intestacy rules, while the remaining estate would be divided among his children, potentially creating a tax bill.

The family could avoid the tax by drawing up a deed of variation to split up the estate, reducing any sum left to the children so it was below the tax threshold. Mayall's family declined to discuss the estate and the apparent lack of a will.

In a separate matter, it was revealed that the writers behind Alan B'Stard, Laurence Marks and Maurice Gran, played a crucial role in getting David Cameron into Downing Street. They lived in the Oxfordshire constituency of Witney, where Cameron would later become MP, and their opinions were respected when it came to selecting Conservative candidates for the area. Despite being committed Labour supporters, they backed David Cameron as the best candidate for the Tories in 2001, which ultimately led to his becoming MP for Witney and later Prime Minister.

The evacuation of Indian nationals and other foreigners from war-torn Sanaa, Yemen, is underway, with Air India playing a significant role in the operation. Passengers, including Indians, Yemenis, and others, scramble onto airport tarmacs, carrying their belongings, and boarding Air India planes with carry-on luggage only. The flight attendants treat the passengers like they are on a vacation flight, offering drinks and maintaining a cheerful demeanor. Many passengers are exhausted and traumatized by the conflict, having left behind their lives in Yemen. Air India has evacuated around 2,500 people from Yemen so far, with flights heading to Djibouti, a small African nation. Some evacuees are also fleeing on boats from port cities like Aden. While the evacuation provides a temporary respite for those affected by the conflict, many leave behind their lives and loved ones in Yemen.

An Italian priest was sacked after an online lover contacted the church authorities with a dossier containing alleged evidence of sex with prostitutes, role play, and explicit gay web chats. The priest allegedly favored sexual role-play scenarios involving his lover playing the disciple Judas Iscariot, and had to atone for his betrayal of Jesus by becoming his slave. This scandal is the latest in a series of sex scandals to engulf the Vatican. The diocese confirmed the priest's dismissal but claimed there were no other prelates involved. The 32-year-old man, an unemployed laborer from Rovigo, said he was contacted by the priest on Facebook and that the priest revealed he was gay during online chats, attempting to seduce the laborer. The priest allegedly said he had organized orgies with priests and a Swiss Guard, but church authorities have not confirmed anyone else's involvement. The laborer claimed that the priest even convinced him to leave his girlfriend. The diocese of Taranto issued a statement saying the priest, who was not part of the Taranto clergy but a member of a religious order, had been removed from pastoral care by bishop Filippo Santoro after verifying the facts. The religious order member is no longer in Taranto, and the statement added that there is no trace of other priests being involved in the scandal.

A new study in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism, even among high-risk children with siblings who have autism. This study, which analyzed data from about 95,000 young people, is the latest in a series of research over the past 15 years that has consistently failed to establish a connection between the MMR vaccine and autism.

Despite the mounting evidence, concerns over vaccine safety persist, partly due to a now-discredited 1998 study by Andrew Wakefield that claimed to find a link between the MMR vaccine and autism. Wakefield's study was later found to be fraudulent, and he was stripped of his medical license.

The new study found that children with older siblings who have autism are less likely to be vaccinated, with MMR vaccination rates of 92% for children with unaffected siblings compared to 86% for children with affected siblings. However, the study found no evidence that vaccines increased autism risk, regardless of whether a sibling had autism or not.

An accompanying editorial by Bryan King emphasizes that the data shows no relationship between MMR and the development of autism in children with or without a sibling who has autism. The editorial notes that numerous studies have consistently shown that the age of onset, severity, and course of autism do not differ between vaccinated and unvaccinated children.

A 12-year-old girl named Jalila was kidnapped by ISIS fighters from her home in Yazidi, Iraq, and experienced horrific abuse. She was tied up, beaten, and raped by seven different fighters over a period of time. Jalila's story is one of many harrowing accounts shared by women who have escaped ISIS captivity. The study by Human Rights Watch found that ISIS fighters were kidnapping women and children, forcing them to convert to Islam, marry, and repeatedly raping them. Children as young as eight have been abducted, raped, and forced into marriage. The report states that these actions amount to war crimes and possibly crimes against humanity. Survivors who managed to escape have attempted suicide and require better medical and psychological support. The UN has found evidence of ISIS committing genocide against the Yazidi minority in Iraq.

A former student at Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina, allegedly opened fire in the campus library on Monday morning, killing one person and injuring others. The suspect, Kenneth Stancil, 20, was a former student who did not graduate from the college. He allegedly entered the building at 8am carrying a long-barreled gun, went up to the third floor, and fired one shot, which killed long-time employee Ron Lane. It is not known whether Stancil and Lane are connected or related. Police have issued a warrant for Stancil's arrest and described him as a white male, approximately 5'11", with a goatee and a tattoo over his left eye. Authorities are urging the public not to approach Stancil, as he is considered extremely dangerous.

The new chief executive of Rotherham council could be paid up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to the negative publicity from the grooming scandal. The council will now offer up to £200,000 to candidates, compared to the £160,000 enjoyed by former chief boss Martin Kimber. The increase in salary is intended to attract candidates despite the council's reputation following a series of resignations and negative reports.

Cesc Fabregas will wear a special protective face mask for Chelsea after breaking his nose during a game against Stoke City. The mask was made by Ortholabsport in Milan, and Fabregas traveled there with Chelsea medical director Paco Biosca to have it fitted. The orthopedic center has previously made masks for players like Fernando Torres, Petr Cech, and Demba Ba. Fabregas could be ready to play against Queens Park Rangers on Sunday if manager Jose Mourinho selects him. However, teammates John Obi Mikel and Diego Costa might not be available for the game, with the former resuming training and the latter expected to miss at least two weeks due to a hamstring problem.

Andros Townsend scored a fantastic goal for England against Italy, which helped the team secure a 1-1 draw. The 23-year-old winger, who has had an up-and-down season, used the criticism from pundits like Paul Merson as motivation. England manager Roy Hodgson continued to show faith in Townsend, who repaid that faith with a brilliant goal.

A husband accused of trying to murder his cheating wife wrote her an extraordinary letter from prison asking her to send him a suit for his trial. Joseph O'Riordan, 73, stabbed his 47-year-old wife Amanda eight times after discovering her affair with a postman. She was left with life-threatening injuries. O'Riordan, who was a councillor at the time, called an ambulance and admitted what he had done during the 999 call. Four months later, while on remand, O'Riordan wrote to his wife asking her to gather his belongings for his trial, including a suit, jumper, and ties.

During questioning, Mrs. O'Riordan sobbed, saying she never wanted to hurt her husband and that the affair was her fault. The case was adjourned for 90 minutes to give her time to regain her composure. O'Riordan's defense team asked if she had been expecting the letter, to which she replied no.

In a pre-recorded police interview, Mrs. O'Riordan described her husband as passionate and vocally volatile but said he had never laid a finger on her before. She thought he might have suffered from mild depression. She also said she and her husband were soulmates, having met in 1991 and married for ten years at the time of the attack.

Mrs. O'Riordan admitted to having a brief affair with a postman, which she said was the trigger for the attack. She said her husband had found out about the affair after hiring a private detective to follow her. O'Riordan pleaded not guilty to attempted murder, and the trial continues.

The UK is set to open its first three proton beam therapy centers, following the successful treatment of cancer-stricken five-year-old Ashya King. Cardiff-based Proton Partners International Ltd will open the centers in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland by 2017, with the first in Cardiff becoming operational next year. The announcement comes after Ashya was given the all-clear following proton beam therapy in Prague. The centers will provide cutting-edge treatment for cancer patients, including those currently treated abroad at a high cost. The development follows discussions between Professor Sir Chris Evans and UK life sciences and healthcare investors, who have committed nearly £100 million in equity finance. Professor Gordon McVie has been appointed chairman of the group, and Professor Karol Sikora will serve as chief medical adviser. The centers will provide proton beam therapy, a highly targeted form of radiotherapy with a lower risk of side effects than conventional treatment. However, it is estimated that only one in 100 people would be suitable for proton beam therapy, and the long-term impact of the procedure is not yet known. The UK government has announced plans to create two NHS proton beam therapy units, which are expected to open in 2018.

Ambulance bosses in the UK are recruiting paramedics from Australia, as they face a shortage of trained staff in Britain. London Ambulance Service has hired 225 paramedics from Sydney and Melbourne, attracting them with £4,500 "golden hello" payments and offering a salary of £30,200. The recruitment process involves a series of practical demonstrations, a written exam, and an interview, with successful candidates receiving job offers within a day.

The NHS is struggling to train enough staff to meet the needs of a rising and ageing population, leading to hospital managers recruiting nurses from Spain and Portugal. The increasing demand on ambulances and the exodus of paramedics to advanced practitioner roles in A&E, GP surgeries, and call centers for the 111 helpline have contributed to the staff shortage.

Other understaffed ambulance services in the UK are also recruiting from abroad, including Poland. The London Ambulance Service has hired 175 paramedics from Australia and New Zealand in September and is considering another recruitment drive later this year. The service calculates that the first recruitment drive saved the NHS £9 million, as it costs £50,000 to train one paramedic in Britain.

Jason Killens, director of operations at London Ambulance Service, said the recruitment from Australia is a temporary solution while they train more people to become paramedics in the UK. The Australian paramedics are attracted by the opportunity to help people and explore Europe.

Chelsea have partnered with Technogym to utilize the latest fitness technology in their pursuit of the Premier League title. The club currently holds a seven-point lead with a game in hand, and players like Eden Hazard, Nemanja Matic, and Kurt Zouma have been seen working out at the state-of-the-art facility at Cobham. The partnership aims to help Chelsea maintain their performance levels in the final seven games of the season. Technogym's equipment is known for its high quality and innovation, and the company's founder Nerio Alessandri believes that both Chelsea and Technogym share a strong dedication to performance. Two Chelsea players, Diego Costa and Eden Hazard, have been nominated for the PFA Player of the Year award, with Hazard being the favorite to win.

This article discusses the findings of two studies on the cognitive abilities of infants. In the first study, 11-month-old babies were shown to have already mastered the fundamentals of physics, as they reacted with surprise to objects that appeared to defy the laws of gravity. When given the opportunity to play with these objects, they attempted to learn more about them by banging a ball on a table and repeatedly dropping a toy car on the floor.

The babies in the study were also shown to have a strong understanding of social situations, as they were able to distinguish between bullying, friendship, and the role of a bystander. These findings suggest that infants are smarter than previously thought and can learn from unexpected situations.

The second study found that babies who could accurately depict the human form at the age of four were more likely to perform better in intelligence tests during their teenage years. Researchers believe that the ability to draw is a uniquely human ability and a sign of cognitive ability, similar to writing.

Manny Pacquiao chose to train outdoors in Los Angeles' Griffith Park on Friday, running along the trail to prepare for his highly-anticipated fight against Floyd Mayweather. He was joined by fitness fanatics and his pet dog Pacman, showcasing his skills with shadow boxing. Pacquiao recently unveiled his multicolored mouth guard, which reads 'MouthGuards for Champions', reflecting his confidence ahead of the $300 million Las Vegas showdown. The 36-year-old focused on his core strength during the outdoor training session, impressing watching spectators.

Biso, a cat who had been stuck in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years, has finally been freed. The cat survived thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo, who fed him daily. A social media campaign brought attention to Biso's plight, and animal rights activists rescued the cat after a lengthy process. However, Biso quickly ran away after being freed, and is still missing.

At least 35 workers have been killed in Yemen after Saudi Arabian warplanes bombed Shiite rebel positions in the Red Sea port city of Hodeida. The airstrikes targeted rebel-controlled army camps and warehouses belonging to a dairy factory, which subsequently caught fire and collapsed, killing and injuring several workers. The attack comes as Saudi Arabia hints at the possibility of a ground invasion in Yemen to force the Iran-backed Shiite rebels, known as Houthis, to allow current president Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi to return to the country. The Houthis have overrun the Yemeni capital, Sanaa, and several provinces, forcing Hadi to flee abroad last week. The ongoing conflict has raised concerns about high civilian casualties, with UNICEF reporting that 62 children were killed and 30 wounded during the fighting in Yemen over the past week.

Hundreds of morning commuters in Boston faced delays on April 20, 2023, after a truck crashed on an elevated highway over subway and rail tracks. The box truck collided with a car on Interstate 93 southbound in the city's Dorchester neighborhood, causing non-life-threatening injuries to both drivers. Officials did not risk running trains under the overhanging truck, so replacement shuttle buses were provided for southbound passengers, leading to long queues. The truck was towed by crane at about 8:30 am, but traffic remained backed up in both directions. The investigation into the incident is ongoing, and no charges have been filed.

Saracens director of rugby Mark McCall praised his young players after their European loss to Clermont, but stated that the club has no intention of overspending in the competitive post-World Cup transfer market. McCall watched a young Saracens team, with five English-qualified forwards in the starting pack, battle against Clermont before losing 13-9. The club's chairman, Nigel Wray, has been advocating for the removal of the salary cap to help Saracens compete at the top level in Europe, raising expectations for a high-profile signing. However, McCall emphasized that the club is not in a rush to sign a "name" player and is focused on finding the right person to improve the team. He believes that the young forwards in the team have a promising future with the club for the next four to five seasons.

The decomposing bodies of four men accused of killing 148 people at a Kenyan university were paraded in front of a large crowd at a primary school. The bodies were driven around Garissa in a pickup truck from the mortuary to Garissa Primary School, where hundreds gathered to view them. Survivor Cynthia Cheroitich, 19, was rescued after spending two days hiding in a wardrobe and drinking body lotion to survive. The attackers were killed at Garissa, but their nationalities and names have not been revealed. The public viewing of the corpses was hoped to help identify the attackers.

Four attackers died at Garissa, but they have not been named and their nationalities have not been revealed. It was hoped that crowds viewing the corpses might identify them. 'I want to see them,' Muna Haji told The Washington Post. 'I want to know that these people are dead. They have killed innocent people.' Arsenal must make a swift decision on Petr Cech this summer or risk losing out on the goalkeeper. Chelsea's Cech looks certain to leave Stamford Bridge at the end of the season after losing his No 1 spot to Thibaut Courtois. Arsene Wenger must be swift with a move for his top goalkeeping target to beat the competition, as Liverpool, Paris Saint-Germain, Roma, and Inter Milan are also interested. However, Arsenal may face obstacles in landing Cech due to his valuation and Chelsea's potential reluctance to sell to a Premier League rival. Cech is expected to have a meeting with Jose Mourinho at the end of the season to confirm his decision to leave west London.

Frankie Dettori will focus on the British Flat season this summer, while Gregory Benoist will ride horses under Sheik Joaan Al Thani's Al Shaqab banner in France. The only exception is Treve, who will continue to be partnered by Thierry Jarnet. The recruitment of Benoist could be seen as a snub for Dettori, but it is said to be due to logistical reasons as Sheik Joaan's operation has expanded. Dettori finished third on Al Shaqab's Moheet in the Novae Bloodstock Craven Stakes at Newmarket. Significant Guineas action took place before racing started when Charlie Hills-trained Acomb Stakes winner Connection put in a decent gallop under William Buick. Retiring champion jump jockey AP McCoy was unplaced on his final ride at Cheltenham but will ride at Ayr for the next two days and is likely to not ride again until his final ride at Sandown's end-of-season meeting.

Lois Lilienstein, co-star of the popular Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," has passed away at the age of 78 due to a rare form of cancer. The show, which aired on CBC in Canada and Nickelodeon in the US, was known for songs like "Skinnamarink" and "Peanut Butter." Lilienstein left the performance trio in 2000.

This video shows French freediving champion Guillaume Néry jumping into Dean's Blue Hole, the world's second-deepest underwater sinkhole, without scuba gear and holding his breath. Although he doesn't reach the bottom, the video is still impressive as he holds his breath for minutes on end. Freediving is a form of underwater diving without breathing equipment, and some free divers can hold their breath for more than 20 minutes. The video was filmed in 2010 by Guillaume's girlfriend and fellow freediver Julie Gautier, at Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas.

A suicide bomber on a motorbike killed at least 33 people and injured more than 100 others in an attack on the Kabul Bank in Jalalabad, Afghanistan. The Islamic State of Iraq and Syria (ISIS) claimed responsibility for the attack, marking their first claim in Afghanistan. The attack targeted government workers collecting their pay at the bank, and the Taliban has distanced themselves from the incident. The United Nations condemned the violence and expressed concerns about the growth of ISIS in the region.

Laura Wells, an Australian plus-size model and environmental scientist, has launched a new eco-friendly swimwear line made entirely of 100 per cent recycled material. The collection, inspired by the ocean and coral reefs, is designed in collaboration with US brand Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy. The line includes one and two-piece suits catering to various shapes and sizes, ranging from 10 to 24. The swimsuits are designed to be both fashion-forward and environmentally friendly, with affordability in mind.

The TrackYourDose app, developed by Germany-based esooka, records personal radiation exposure, including exposure from medical examinations, changes in location, and flights. The app, available for £1.49 ($1.99) on iOS, uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists from the Physikalisch-Technische Bundesanstalt (PTB) in Germany and the University Oulu, Finland.

The app takes into account cosmic radiation at flight altitudes, geographical location, flight altitude, and solar activity. It can measure all relevant types of radiation, including neutron radiation produced in the atmosphere. Users enter their flight details and solar activity, which is inputted using a neutron monitor from the University of Oulu in Finland.

A ten-hour flight across the North Atlantic, for instance, results in a radiation exposure of between 50 µSv to 100 µSv. This is compared to 6 µSv from a dentist's X-ray or 100 µSv from a mammogram. Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility linked to a foodborne illness that caused the deaths of three people. The company is conducting an investigation to determine the exact cause of the contamination. Ten recalled products were from a production line at a plant in Brenham, Texas, and were shipped to institutional accounts in 23 states. The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommends that consumers do not eat any Blue Bell brand products made at the Oklahoma facility. The recall began after five patients at a Kansas hospital became ill with listeriosis, a life-threatening infection caused by Listeria monocytogenes. The disease primarily affects pregnant women, newborns, older adults, and people with weakened immune systems. The CDC has identified six patients with listeriosis between 2010 and 2014 that was indistinguishable from that found in the contaminated ice cream product. Blue Bell says it will conduct a thorough examination of the Oklahoma plant and make necessary improvements before resuming operations.

Jon Hamm, star of the hit TV series Mad Men, has been accused of participating in a brutal hazing incident during his college years at the University of Texas at Austin. According to court documents, Hamm and other fraternity members allegedly beat and dragged a pledge by his genitals, set his pants on fire, and subjected him to other forms of torture in 1990. The actor was charged with assault but managed to get the charges dismissed. The hazing incident led to the shutdown of the Sigma Nu fraternity at the university. Despite the dark past, Hamm's friend claims that the hazing incident was an isolated event and that the actor has since made efforts to become a better person. Hamm has recently admitted that playing the complex role of Don Draper has taken its toll on his psyche, but he loves working with the people on the show. As he reflects on being typecast as a dark, brooding character, Hamm hopes to distance himself from that persona in future roles.

The ongoing dispute over the Falkland Islands has escalated, with Argentina taking legal action against British oil companies exploring off the islands' coast. Argentine President Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner has vowed to reclaim the islands, which Argentina calls the Malvinas, prompting the UK government to pledge increased defense spending. The UK Foreign Office has summoned the Argentine ambassador, and the two countries have exchanged diplomatic tensions. The UK defends the Falklands' right to explore their resources and maintains that the islands are British territory.

A Delta Air Lines flight experienced an incident at LaGuardia Airport when an odor of smoke was reported by the crew after the plane landed. Firefighters in full protective suits surrounded the aircraft and used a thermal imaging camera to locate a potential heat source. Passengers were kept on board for about 45 minutes before they were allowed to deplane normally. The plane was taken out of service for inspection and maintenance.

David Luiz, the injured Paris Saint-Germain defender, has taken the phrase "twiddling my hair" literally, as seen in his latest Instagram post. He sports a new hairdo in the style of a man bun. Luiz suffered a torn hamstring during Sunday's match against Marseille and will be out for at least four weeks. His new hairstyle has become a source of amusement for his teammates, especially Lucas Moura, who jokingly referred to it in an Instagram post. While Luiz's hair might be a fun topic for his teammates, his injury is a serious concern for manager Laurent Blanc, as PSG seeks Ligue 1 and Champions League glory this season. Luiz will miss both legs of their quarter-final tie against Barcelona in Europe and potentially eight league matches.

US President Barack Obama emphasized the importance of diplomacy in dealing with Iran's nuclear program, stating that a comprehensive, long-term deal is the best option. He acknowledged that there will be a robust debate in the United States and promised to keep Congress informed about the deal's substance. Critics, including Republican opponents in Congress and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, have expressed concerns that the deal may give too much away and threaten the security of the region. However, Obama highlighted the rigorous inspections included in the agreement, which are based on unprecedented verification. The outline of the deal requires Iran to significantly reduce its centrifuges in exchange for the suspension of sanctions. Final negotiations for the deal are expected to be completed by June 30.

A 12-year-old girl battling leukemia for two years was kicked out of St. Joseph's Middle School in Battle Creek, Michigan, for her poor attendance and low academic performance. The school claims to have made many accommodations for the girl, but none seemed to help her enough. The girl's mother is heartbroken and believes her daughter's recovery will take time, even though she is no longer receiving cancer treatment. The girl has attended Battle Creek Catholic Schools her whole life and felt normal at school. She was diagnosed with leukemia in 2012 and still feels ill, which affects her attendance and schoolwork. The school says she attended only 32 days this school year. The girl's parents feel the school failed their child and filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights. The family is waiting for a response.

Researchers have discovered that passive smoking affects plants, causing them to absorb nicotine from contaminated soil and smoke. This finding may explain high nicotine levels in certain spices, herbal teas, and medicinal plants, even though nicotine is banned in insecticides. In a series of experiments, peppermint plants were exposed to cigarette smoke, resulting in high nicotine concentrations. The study suggests that nicotine levels in plants may come from sources other than illegal insecticides and demonstrates the horizontal transfer of natural products between plants. This discovery sheds light on the success of farming practices like crop rotation and co-cultivation.

This video shows a fierce battle between two male chameleons fighting for a female mate near the Amber Mountain National Park in Madagascar. The aggressive chameleon chases his rival out of the tree and along a concrete wall, biting him and causing pain. The defeated chameleon struggles to escape, eventually crawling across a concrete wall, while the other chameleon slowly gives chase. The video ends with both chameleons climbing onto a tree branch and becoming obscured by leaves.

Scotland youth international Jack Cosgrove has agreed to join Edinburgh next season on a two-year deal. The 20-year-old Worcester Warriors prop, who has been capped nine times for the Dark Blues Under 20s side, is looking forward to joining the Murrayfield outfit, which has a strong reputation among his fellow Scotland under 20 players. Cosgrove, known for his strong set-piece game, aims to add something extra to the squad and learn from players like Alasdair Dickinson. The prop is excited about the prospect of joining the club, which is currently in the European Cup Final.

Aaron Hernandez, a former NFL player who was convicted of murder, has been sentenced to life in prison without parole. He has been transferred to Cedar Junction state prison in Massachusetts and will later be moved to the maximum security Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center. Hernandez is reportedly on suicide watch and is being held separately from other prisoners. He has been identified as a user of "angel dust," a hallucinogenic drug known to cause violent outbursts and paranoia.

Sources claim that Hernandez was using the drug for at least a year before the murder of Odin Lloyd, for which he was convicted. The drug is said to have made him aggressive and unpleasant, with friends and acquaintances noting a change in his behavior.

Before his arrest, Hernandez lived a luxurious life, with a $1.3 million mansion and a lifestyle that included heavy drinking and partying. However, his friends reported that he became more aggressive and arrogant as his fame and wealth grew.

Hernandez's drug use and the effects it had on his behavior are now a focus of the investigation into his crimes. The NFL will likely investigate how a heavy drug user could have avoided detection in their drug testing programs.

Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini has confirmed that the club's young Academy players are not yet ready to step into the first-team squad, which may lead to players like Jason Denayer being recalled from loan deals. Celtic is keen to retain Denayer, who has impressed during his loan spell, but faces an uphill battle due to City's need to invest in homegrown talent. Current Premier League regulations require clubs to carry a minimum of eight homegrown players, and Denayer, though from Belgium, falls into this category. Pellegrini acknowledges the importance of the Academy but stresses the need for patience in developing young players. The future of Denayer and other young City professionals on loan, such as Karim Rekik and Marcos Lopes, remains uncertain as City considers its options for next season.

Ander Herrera, a Manchester United midfielder, revealed in a Q&A video that he wears his full name on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons, following his successful spell at Athletic Bilbao. He believes that using his full name has been lucky for him, as he had a great three years at Bilbao. After a slow start at United, Herrera has recently impressed with a series of strong performances, contributing to the team's improved results. He hopes to show more emotion as the team pursues silverware in the future.

Porto supporters gave their team a hero's welcome following their 6-1 defeat at Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-finals, despite the team's disappointing performance. Fans mobbed the squad, congratulating them on their run in the tournament, and Porto star striker Jackson Martinez and Ricardo Quaresma looked perplexed as they were hugged by fans. It was the first time since the 2008-09 season that Porto had reached the Champions League quarter-finals. Bayern Munich won the tie emphatically, with goals from Thomas Muller, Thiago Alcantara, Jerome Boateng, Xabi Alonso, and a double from Robert Lewandowski. Porto coach Julen Lopetegui admitted that his side were beaten by a much better team and that they have to accept the defeat, but can still be proud of their performance in the Champions League.

The BBC has been criticized for creating a computer game called Syrian Journey, which simulates the ordeal of Syrian refugees fleeing their war-torn country. The game, available on the BBC website, leads players through the difficult decisions refugees face while trying to escape Syria and reach Europe. Critics argue that the game turns the suffering of millions into a children's game and is in poor taste. The game often ends with refugees drowning in the Mediterranean or being sold to militia. The BBC defended the game, saying it aims to show audiences the choices faced by thousands of Syrian families every day. Despite the controversy, the game has received over a million online hits a week.

Boston Marathon bomber Dzhokar Tsarnaev has been given another chance by his victims Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who lost limbs in the 2013 attack. The couple has joined the Richard family in opposing the death penalty for Tsarnaev, urging others to overcome the urge for vengeance. The couple's statement comes after the family of Martin Richard, who was killed in the blast, made a similar appeal. A jury will decide Tsarnaev's sentence this week, with options of death or life in prison without parole.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife, Dr. Ayse Giray, who claimed half of the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement occurred just before a court ruling on whether Giray could be retroactively named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company, Euphrates. Although the two were married for only two years in the 1990s and the company was not an issue in their divorce, Giray based her claim on handwritten notes that she believed confirmed financial support from Ulukaya. Chobani settled the case to avoid potentially losing $1 billion in assets. Despite the settlement, Ulukaya still faces business challenges, including a possible replacement as CEO due to a 2013 product recall that led to negative EBITDA of $87 million and other issues related to the construction of the company's Idaho factory.

Diego Costa is aiming to make a comeback from his latest hamstring injury for Chelsea's crucial clash against Arsenal on April 26. The Spain international limped off after just 11 minutes in Chelsea's 2-1 win over Stoke on Saturday and is expected to miss two weeks. Costa will likely miss games against Queens Park Rangers and Manchester United but is determined to play against Arsenal, which could be a pivotal match in the title race. Chelsea may consider giving Costa an extended break between now and the end of the season to help him overcome his hamstring problems, depending on how the title race develops.

The England C team, which has operated since 1979 and represents non-league players under 23, is facing the axe as part of FA chairman Greg Dyke's spending review. Dyke aims to save £30 million to fund grassroots football reforms, including the construction of 3G pitches in urban coaching hubs. England C's future is uncertain, as the FA considers it an area of potential savings. The team, managed by Paul Fairclough, has played friendly matches in various locations, but no official fixtures are planned. Some players who have represented England C have gone on to play for their respective countries at the senior level, such as George Boyd (Scotland), Craig Mackail-Smith (Scotland), and Steve Morison (Wales).

James Haskell, an England flanker and London Wasps captain, showed off his inner Iron Man in a serious-looking Instagram post, joining in on the hype for the new Avengers: Age of Ultron movie. The highly-anticipated movie premiered at Westfield London shopping centre, with fans queuing up to see the A-list cast, including Robert Downey Jr., Chris Hemsworth, and Scarlett Johansson. Haskell, who first joined Wasps in 2002 and has since played for various clubs around the world, returned to the club in 2012 and has become a key member of the England squad with 57 caps to-date.

Police are urging witnesses to come forward after a middle-aged woman was filmed launching a racist tirade against a Muslim woman on a Sydney train. Stacey Eden, 23, stood up for the Muslim woman and her partner, recording the incident and defending the couple against the bullying. In the video, Eden can be heard saying, "She wears it [hijab] for herself, OK!" and "It doesn't matter what they're doing... Have some respect, have some respect." The Muslim couple thanked Eden for her support, and she missed her stop to ensure their safety. Police have not received any reports of the incident, but Sydney Trains and the Islamophobia Register Australia have praised Eden's actions. The group said incidents of abuse against Muslim women are becoming more common and encouraged others to stand up against racial or religious vilification.

The mother of Odin Lloyd, Ursula Ward, is moving forward with a civil lawsuit against Aaron Hernandez, the man convicted of killing her son. Ward's lawyer, Douglas Sheff, said Hernandez will be called to testify during the wrongful death suit, and Ward wants to look him in the eye when he does. Hernandez was convicted of first-degree murder on April 15 for the 2013 shooting death of Lloyd.

The lawsuit, filed in December 2013, was put on hold during the criminal trial, but now Ward's lawyers plan to resume the case to hunt down Hernandez's assets. The suit seeks unspecified damages, and while an appeal is automatic in the criminal case, the Patriots and Ward's lawyers have agreed that if the team owes Hernandez more money, it will not pay him directly but will instead hold onto the money and alert them and the court.

Britain has discovered oil in the Falkland Islands, a development that could escalate tensions with Argentina, which also claims ownership of the islands. The discovery, announced by British firms Premier Oil, Rockhopper Exploration, and Falkland Oil & Gas, is estimated to contain 100 million barrels of oil and was made at the Zebedee exploratory well, located 130 kilometers north of the Falklands. Argentina has threatened to prosecute oil companies operating in the area, claiming they are acting illegally in Argentine territory. The discovery comes just days after UK Defense Secretary Michael Fallon warned of a "very live threat" from Argentina, and amid heightened tensions on the 33rd anniversary of the Falklands War.

A three-legged cat named Freeman was brutally mauled to death by two dogs in a horrific attack captured on CCTV. The attack took place in the front garden of the cat's owner, Tracy Lynch, in Tarring, West Sussex. A woman, believed to be the dogs' owner, arrived in a blue car, called over the dogs, and left the cat to die in agony. The 90-second attack was passed on to the police, who are now investigating. The cat's owner and neighbors are devastated by the incident, as the cat was a beloved neighborhood character.

A Chinese woman named Zhu Diandian has become an internet sensation after sharing her life with her pet pig, Five Flowers. She has raised the pig since it was a piglet, and now at 187lbs (13st), their bond remains strong. Zhu Diandian and Five Flowers sleep together every day, and her husband is reportedly tolerant of the relationship. However, their pet dog is not as accepting, often peering at the pig through a baby gate that keeps the dog out of the bedroom. Zhu Diandian's pictures have garnered significant attention in China, with netizens commenting on the unusual pet bond. The owner's surname, Zhu, sounds like "pig" in Mandarin, which may be the reason for her love of the animal. The pig is dressed in clothes, taken for walks, and even has a green T-shirt and body harness. Zhu Diandian ensures Five Flowers is well taken care of, even leading the pig to the bath with a trail of green vegetables. The woman works at a publishing company in Beijing and has almost 40,000 followers on Weibo. Her latest photos of Five Flowers in bed have received 13,000 retweets and almost 9,000 comments, most of which are supportive of her unique pet.
